    story: '''
Erlang Shen, yang bernama asli Yang Jian, lahir dari perkawinan terlarang antara adik perempuan Kaisar Giok dan seorang pemuda fana bernama Yang Tianyou. Karena melanggar hukum langit dengan mencintai manusia, sang ibu dihukum dan dipenjarakan di bawah Gunung Tao, sementara Yang Jian tumbuh dengan mata ketiga yang misterius terpancang vertikal di tengah dahinya—tanda kekuatan sakti yang membedakannya dari dewa lain. Sebagian tradisi juga menyatukan sosoknya dengan Li Erlang, putra insinyur legendaris Li Bing yang menaklukkan banjir Sungai Min di Sichuan, sehingga Erlang Shen dikenal sekaligus sebagai keponakan Kaisar Giok dan pahlawan pengendali bencana air bagi rakyat jelata.

Mata ketiganya mampu menembus segala ilusi, penyamaran, dan kejahatan tersembunyi, menjadikannya salah satu pendeteksi kebenaran paling tajam di seluruh Kahyangan, sekaligus mampu memancarkan cahaya menyilaukan yang melumpuhkan musuh. Sebagai panglima perang bergelar dewa, ia memimpin pasukan enam bersaudara Gunung Mei serta memegang tombak bermata tiga berujung ganda, ditemani seekor anjing langit setia bernama Xiaotian Quan yang turut bertarung di sisinya. Ia juga dipuja sebagai pelindung dari banjir dan bencana air, mewarisi peran sebagai penjaga irigasi dan pengendali sungai, sehingga kuil-kuilnya banyak ditemukan di kawasan Sichuan yang rawan banjir sejak zaman kuno.

Kisahnya yang paling melegenda adalah duel sengitnya melawan Sun Wukong dalam Kera Sakti, ketika Kaisar Giok mengutusnya untuk menangkap si kera pemberontak yang telah mengacaukan Kahyangan. Keduanya bertarung dengan saling bertukar wujud—berubah menjadi burung, ikan, ular, bahkan kuil—dalam pertarungan transformasi yang legendaris, hingga akhirnya Erlang Shen berhasil menjatuhkan Sun Wukong berkat bantuan gelang berlian Laozi dan gigitan Xiaotian Quan. Dalam kisah lain, ia justru dikenal karena mengurung adiknya sendiri di bawah Gunung Hua karena menikah dengan manusia—sebuah nasib ironis yang kelak dipatahkan oleh keponakannya, Chenxiang, yang membelah gunung untuk membebaskan ibunya. Hingga kini Erlang Shen tetap dipuja sebagai pelindung dari bencana air dan simbol keadilan tegas dalam opera serta cerita rakyat Tiongkok.''',
    storyEn: '''
Erlang Shen, whose personal name is Yang Jian, was born of a forbidden union between the Jade Emperor's younger sister and a mortal man named Yang Tianyou. Because loving a human violated the laws of Heaven, his mother was punished and imprisoned beneath Mount Tao, while the young Yang Jian grew up bearing a mysterious third eye set vertically in the center of his forehead—a mark of the extraordinary power that set him apart from other gods. Some traditions also merge him with Li Erlang, son of the legendary engineer Li Bing who tamed the flooding Min River in Sichuan, so that Erlang Shen is remembered both as the Jade Emperor's nephew and as a folk hero who mastered devastating floods on behalf of ordinary people.

His third eye can pierce through any illusion, disguise, or hidden evil, making him one of the sharpest detectors of truth in all of Heaven, and it can also unleash a blinding beam capable of stunning enemies outright. As a warrior-general among the gods, he commands the six sworn brothers of Mount Mei and wields a three-pointed, double-edged lance, accompanied always by his loyal celestial hound Xiaotian Quan, who fights faithfully at his side. He is also venerated as a protector against floods and water disasters, inheriting a role as guardian of irrigation and river control, which is why his temples remain concentrated in flood-prone Sichuan since ancient times.

His most celebrated tale is his fierce duel with Sun Wukong in Journey to the West, when the Jade Emperor dispatched him to capture the rebellious Monkey King who had thrown Heaven into disorder. The two traded shapes in a legendary contest of transformation—becoming birds, fish, snakes, even a temple—until Erlang Shen finally overpowered Sun Wukong with the help of Laozi's diamond bracelet and a well-timed bite from Xiaotian Quan. In another well-known story, he is the one who imprisons his own younger sister beneath Mount Hua for marrying a mortal man—an irony later undone by his nephew Chenxiang, who splits the mountain open to free his mother. Erlang Shen remains venerated today as a guardian against flooding and a symbol of unyielding justice in Chinese opera and folklore.''',
